The capstone project provides for a culminating educational experience for the BBA in Organizational Management candidate.  This project is designed for the student to apply all of the knowledge and skills learned in earlier courses and from life experiences.  The capstone project is expected to be one of the most ambitious research, writing, and creative effort of the undergraduate experience.  The project is expected to address a problem related to the student's work experience or a business related vocation.  In any event, the project must be on a business related topic.  The course is designed to help the student identify an acceptable thesis topic, locate sources in information, and initiate and complete the research project.  The student is expected to make a presentation of findings, and to submit final copies of the project to the thesis advisor.

management at the individual, team, and organizational levels. This course also presents a comprehensive, integrative, and practical focus on leadership andmanagement. It includes identification of current leadership styles and examples as well as contemporary perspectives on ethics, organizational culture, diversity, learning organizations, strategic leadership, crisis leadership, networking, and coaching.

This course provides students an introduction to the sociological study of religious phenomena.  It presents several perspective views within sociology and the relationship to religion as a legitimate social institution in society.  Views of major theorights such as Durkheim, Weber, Troeltsch and contemporary others will be discussed.  Modern socio-religious issues such as secularization, fundamentalism, televangelism, new religious movements, globalization, and the relations between religion and race, class, and gender will be addressed.

Prerequisite: RELI 3370

This class explores specific writings of the Hebrew Bible in depth. Students apply their knowledge of exegetical tools and methods to specific books or groups of books. The scope of the class varies from semester to semester.

Prerequisite: Span 3315 with at least a grade of C or permission of the instructor. Survey: Spanish American novels written between the second and third decades of the twentieth century that articulate personifications of forces of nature as well as social and cultural trends acting on the lives and paths of the main characters of texts. Also Afro-Hispanic representative poetry articulating its ethnic view in these decades. Will conduct intensive reading and different literary approaches to these novels and poetry in order to find their literary meanings in their respective aesthetics.

This course is designed to study the development of higher education in the United States, including the forces that have shaped institutions and institutional culture and practice, identification of the significant events and philosophies that have influenced the evolution of higher education institutions, and analysis of the implications of these for practice and the future of higher education; an exploration of the various types of institutions: HBCUs, community colleges, state, private, faith-based, and single-gendered colleges.

The course uses quantitative analysis to instruct the effective planning and deployment of information technology [IT] in management processes. It examines the alignment of IT and data processing in creating business value, business process analysis, IT portfolio management, online analytical processing, and data mining application tools.
The course teaches accounting reporting and the use of accounting information in aiding management decision-making.

CRS_TITLE: Advanced Overview of  Crim Just Sys
CATALOG_TEXT: A comprehensive overview of the criminal justice system from law enforcement through courts and corrections, with particular emphasis on their historical perspectives, present trends, and likely future developments.
An in-depth coverage of concepts of crime, law, and criminology, as well as theories of crime causation and typologies.

The course centers on managerial principles, functions, and practices while emphasizing theories related to contemporary issues and their implications in understanding individuals' and groups' organizational behavior. Topics include individual differences in motivation, perception, culture and learning style, group and organizational dynamics, and the impact of organizational structure and culture on behavior. In addition, leadership techniques for influencing other corporate members, creative problem-solving and decision-making, ethics, and values-based management are covered. In addition, the students will study formulation and implementation issues related to conceptualizing, developing, and managing successful new ventures. The emphasis of this course is on applying and synthesizing concepts and techniques from functional areas of strategic management, finance, accounting, managerial economics, marketing, operations management, and organizational behavior in the context of new venture development.

The course studies the individual firm apart from the entire industry. The topics include the pricing process, the nature of the market, changes in the prices of the agents of production used by individual firms, problems and policies of business planning, forecasting dynamics, conditions, and business risks.

The course focuses on formulating marketing strategies at the strategic management level of the organization. Analytic skills to solve marketing problems and to address marketing opportunities associated with multi-national marketing issues in the context of multi-product, multi-functional consumer, and industrial organizations are emphasized. The course offers a systematic analysis and evaluation of the firm's resources, capabilities, competition, market position, and external environment to develop positions of competitive advantage and superior financial performance.

The course analyzes ethical standards, concepts, principles, and practices prevailing in business environments. It combines the theoretical foundations of a business start-up with the conduct of entrepreneurial activities related to accountability and the social environment.

The course integrates prior learning in leadership, organizational policy, accounting, finance, marketing, IT, and quantitative analysis using cases illustrating students ' strategic decision-making skills.
The purpose of this course is to differentiate the process of effective decision-making, create better teams, and develop leadership skills and knowledge conducive to a positive working atmosphere.

CRS_TITLE: Advanced Seminar in Court Systems a
CATALOG_TEXT: A comprehensive coverage of the court systems, including local, state, and federal courts

In-depth examination of contemporary issues and trends in the criminal justice field. This course will also bring practice to campus with workshops from field experts organized by the Criminal Justice Department at Wiley University.

An in-depth overview of research methodology that includes an introduction to and structuring of criminal 

justice inquiry, modes of observation, and application and analysis.

Descriptive and inferential statistical concepts and techniques commonly used in educational research. An extensive survey of the theoretical principles of organizational behavior and institutional culture applied to a functional examination of administrative roles in higher education.  This course will explore the operational structure of campuses, including institutional advancement and the business function of higher education institutions.

CRS_TITLE: Finance and Budgeting in Higher Edu
CATALOG_TEXT: Introduction to major elements of budgeting and finance in higher education. Designed to comprehensively address the budget process in colleges and universities, as well as the impact of budget activities on all areas of planning and operations within a higher education institution.

Supervised professional activities in post-secondary teaching, research, or administration. This course connects theory to practice while participating in an active learning experience supervised by an approved university representative.

CRS_TITLE: Student Risk Management in Higher E
CATALOG_TEXT: Legal aspects and risk management of student-related issues in higher education. Topics include federal and state laws and their legal implications as they relate to areas of student rights and responsibilities, privacy, freedom of speech, academic freedom, due process, and harassment.
An extensive analysis of administrative and management skills applicable to criminal justice organizations, including models and best practices in the field.

Criminal Justice Statistics is a survey course designed to introduce undergraduate students to a wide range of statistical techniques used in the social

sciences. This course is a general survey of statistical methods used in the criminal justice field. It begins with a study of descriptive research techniques,

with an emphasis on the design and statistical analysis of descriptive experimentation. Topics will include central tendency and dispersion,

probability theory, frequency distributions and percentiles, correlation and regression, and descriptive research design. Throughout the course, considerable emphasis will be placed on practical application and interpretation of the statistical procedures covered.

This course will aid in the advancement of the students skills in research methodology. It is designed to help adult learners become more aware of their

own particular perspective, to gain insight into minority group positions and feelings, to be able to consider events from more than one viewpoint, and to

apply diversity awareness skills in order to increase their effectiveness and safety on the job.

An introductory methods course designed for Early Childhood Education majors, focusing on developmentally appropriate strategies for teaching mathematics in PreKGrade 6. Aligned with the Texas Essential Knowledge and Skills (TEKS) and Texas Education Agency (TEA) educator standards, the course emphasizes conceptual understanding, problem-solving, and equitable instructional practices. Topics include number sense, operations, algebraic thinking, set theory, proportional reasoning, measurement, and geometry. Candidates will explore the use of manipulatives, assessment tools, and digital resources to support diverse learners and meet state teaching competencies.

A hands-on, instructional methods course designed for Mathematics Education majors preparing to teach middle and high school grades. The course focuses on effective strategies for teaching and assessing key secondary mathematics concepts, including algebra and algebraic reasoning, introductory number theory, set theory, and geometry. Aligned with the Texas Essential Knowledge and Skills (TEKS) and Texas Education Agency (TEA) educator standards, the course emphasizes mathematical justification, reasoning, and discourse as central components of classroom practice. Candidates will engage in practice-based learning, lesson planning, and reflective analysis to support student understanding and mastery of secondary math content. 



Enrollment is limited to education majors.

This course analyzes the many dimensions of new venture creation and growth. In addition, the students will study formulation and implementation issues related to conceptualizing, developing, and managing successful new ventures. The emphasis of this course is on applying and synthesizing concepts and techniques from functional areas of strategic management, finance, accounting, managerial economics, marketing, operations management, and organizational behavior in the context of new venture development.

This course provides a comprehensive examination of African American history from the Trans-Atlantic Slave Trade to the end of the American Civil War in 1865. We will explore the forced migration of African peoples, their experiences in bondage, resistance and abolition movements, and the impact of the Civil War on African American lives. We will draw from a variety of primary and secondary sources, including historical texts, literature, music, and art, to understand the complexities of this period.

This course examines the history of African Americans from the Reconstruction Era (1865-1877) through the present day. We will explore key themes such as the struggle for civil rights, the development of African American culture, the impact of segregation, and contemporary movements for justice. Students will engage with primary sources, scholarly literature, and artistic expressions to gain a nuanced understanding of African American experiences during this transformative period

The course supports institutional goals of academic excellence, equity, and community engagement, and aligns with President Feltons vision for global impact through exceptional scholarship. It provides first-year honors students with a structured experience that cultivates critical thinking, leadership development, and cultural literacy. The course also reinforces Wiley Universitys mission and honors the legacy of Thelma Dewitty, Wiley alumna and civil rights pioneer.

This interdisciplinary seminar focuses on applied leadership in ethical, civic, and global contexts. Students will analyze case studies of leadership in crisis, engage in advocacy and service-learning, and practice skills of negotiation, conflict resolution, and intercultural communication. Emphasizing resilience in action, the course challenges students to integrate their cultural identity and vocational purpose with leadership practices that address both local and global challenges.

This course equips students with the foundational knowledge, strategic understanding, and performance skills necessary to coach and officiate team sports including football, basketball, volleyball, and baseball. Students will analyze game theory, learn rule enforcement, develop ethical decision-making, and participate in laboratory sessions to coach and officiate scrimmage settings. Emphasis will be placed on leadership, classroom management, record-keeping, and the integration of literacy and numeracy in physical education settings.

The only constant in our world today is change.  Often change leads to conflict.  However,  the absence of conflict leads to stagnation.  Harnessing and directing the power of conflict as opportunity is a skill all leades need to develop.

Leaders learn by doing with others.  Mentoring is an ancient path by which apprentices become craftsmen.  This ia a Christian model in many churches and has many benefits both practical and spiritual for training new Christian leaders.
